{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604616/1945110201/0725.xml":{"full_text":"Army Investigates\nForced March ot PWs\nOn Fairfax Highway\nCapt. Joseph C. Bennett, Fairfax\nCounty farm placement manager\nemployed by the State Extension\nService, has resigned in protest over\nthe forced march Wednesday night\nof three German prisoners of war\nalong a Virginia public highway,\ncarrying bundles of rocks on their\nbacks, 11 was revealed today.\nAt the same time an investigation\nhas been launched by the 3d Corpe\nArea, and the Provost Marshal Of n\neral's office.\nPersons living on Route 50, which\npasses near the farm labor camp\nfor 190 German POWs, lodged a\ncomplaint and the Army issued a\nregional order yesterday that hence\nforth discipline will be confined to\nthe reservation proper.\nThinks March Violated Code.\nCapt. Bennett, a retired Marine\nCorps officer, whose job It has been\nto find farm work for the prisoners,\nsaid he witnessed the march which\nhe said he was certain was contrary\nto the Geneva Convention,\nArmy officials said the three\nprisoners had done less than their\nquota of work that day on a farm\nshucking corn and rather than\n\"waste\" farm time by placing them\nIn confinement the marching order\nwas ffiv^n\n\"The weight of the pecks was\n\u00abbout 60 pounds,\" explained Maj.\nAlbert P. Hinckley, In charge of the\nbase prisoner of war camp in Front\nRoyal, under whose jurisdiction the\nFairfax carftp and seven others\ncome. \"That is equivalent to a\nstandard Ajmy pack. Our own\nprisoners can be given the punish\nment of marching with a full pack,\nso there is nothing in the Geneve\nConvention which outlaws such dis\ncipline for prisoners of war.\nOpinion Divided on Treatment.\n\"The only error committed was in\nmarching the men on a highway.\nThe commander may have thought\nthe rule against military forma\ntions in prisoner camps prohibited\nthe marching inside. However, I\nhave cautioned him against using\nthe highways for that sort of thing\nagain.\"\nAt the same time he pointed out\n\u2666hat the public is \"equally divided\"\non the question of punishment for\nprisoners. Daily, he said, he gets\nboth complaints that discipline is\ntoo severe and that prisoners are be\ning coddled.\nThe prisoners have been at Fair-\nfax since June to help out farmers\nin the area. The contract the Army\nmade with the county for this work\nexpires December 1.\nU. S. Chamber Slates\nMarketing Conferences\nThe United States Chamber \u03bf f\nCommerce will hold a series of mar- j\nketing conferences designed to tell\ndistributors how they can sustain a\nvolume of postwar business exceed\ning the best prewar level by 30 to 50\nper cent, it was announced today.\nThe meetings, to be held in widely\nseparated cities, will begin February\n11 and continue on four successive\ndates ending March 4.\nEconomists estimate that unless\nthe distribution goal is achieved,\nconsumption cannot keep place with\nReduction possibilities, and depres\nsion and unemployment will follow,\nit was explained.\nPalestine\n'Continued From First Page.)*\ndeal with the uprising but \"both the\nPalestine police and the forces have\n\u03bb difficult and delicate task co per\nform.\"\nMr. Hall told Commons casualties\nin the outbreaks in Palestine were\nfive killed and at least eight wound\ned, adding that because of the wide\nspread nature of the attacks, re\nports on them were incomplete.\nA Jerusalem dispatch said the\nerection of four new Jewish settle\nments was begun this morning in\nPalestine, two in Galilee and the\nother two in the coastal plain be\ntween Tel Aviv and Haifa.\nJews Have laken Offensive,\nPalestine Paper Says\nJERUSALEM, Nov. 2 (/P).\u2014'The\nPalestine Post asserted today that\noutbursts of violence which para\nlyzed Palestine's railroads and cost\nat least five lives yesterday indi\ncated \"the Jews have gone over from\ndefensive to offensive action\" in\ntheir campaign for revision of the\nBritish white paper quota restrict\ning Jewish immigration.\n\"Resistance has new emerged as\na. primary challenge,\" declared the\npaper in a lengthy editorial com\nmenting on the outbreaks, which a\nBritish military communique blamed\non Jewish elements.\n\"These acts of desperation repre\nsent a new, if not unexpected, step\nin defiance which the Jewish people\nwere driven to proclaim because it\nwas clear that the white paper, far\nfrom being revoked, was to be con\ntinued in force the editorial\ndeclared.\n\"Unless there is a change of heart\nin London or both in London and\nWashington, the alarming prospect\nmust be faced (of) a people\nwho consider that a fight for their\nvery lives has been forced upon\nthem,\" the paper concluded.\nThe situation remainec tense In\nPalestine. By command of Maj.\nGen. John d'Arcy, British com\nmander, movement of all motor\ntraffic between 10 pjm. and 6 ajn.\nwas banned, except in municipal\nareas.\n\u03b1\u03c0 underground radio siauon. ae-\nscribing itself as \"The Voice of\nJewish Resistance,\" promised a\nHebrew resistance group communi\nque would be issued today. It as\nserted that the Palestine Jews have\nno intention of attacking the Arabs. 1\nPalestine Terror Deplored j\nBy Zionist Spokesman\nThe reported terrorism in Palestine\nwas deplored here today by spokes\nmen for the American Zionist Emer- i\ngency Council, who said, however,\nthe Jews were becoming increasingly\nindignant over British policy admin- i\nistering their mandate there.\nDr. Benjamin Akzin, in charge of\nthe council's Washington office, said:\n\"We all deplore the violence in Pal\nestine. But it is getting more and\nmore difficult to restrain the Jewish\npeople there. They are smarting\nunder the restrictions imposed by\nthe British in the illegal White\nPaper still in effect.\"\nNews of District Area Men in Armed Forces\nKilled\nJuges Vachel Scott, seaman Z/c,\nU. S. N. R., only eon of Mr. and Mrs.\nJulian Seal Scott, 1245 Talbert street\nS.E., has been \u039b\nlisted by the\nNavv Depart\nment as killed in j\nSeaman Scott \u03b9\ning since March S\n19, when the air- W&\u00b7 I\ncraft carrier^ \u20141\nFran klin was \u039a m\ndamaged in ac- |p ;MSt\u00e0 \u039b\ntion in Asiatic si* s\nwaters. He left\ntor overseas duty\nIn February.\nThe 22-year\nold seaman Was Seaman Scott.\nborn in Washington and had at\ntended An&costia High School and\nAbingdon Academy, Abingdon, Va.\nHe entered the Navy In August, 1942.\nSafe\nWallace Cornelius Webb, radio\nman 1/c, U. S. N., has been liberated\n'rom a Japanese prison camp, ac\ncording to a Navy Department an\nnouncement. He is the son of Mrs.\n0. S. Brietenbach. 49 Strathmeade\nstreet, Palls Church, Va.\nInductees\nNine Washington men were\nscheduled to report for induction\ninto the armed forces today, selec\ntive service headquarters announced.\nThe men's names follow: Gladstone\nBaltimore, Warren R. Churchill,\nAlfred Durham, Leon F. Harris,\nJasper L. Reed. Alexander Reese\nDonald N. Cooper, William Barge,\njr.; Samuel L. Jones.\nDischarged\nDistrict men discharged from the\nArmy at Port Meade.\nPvt. Irving C. Chtlds. S38V4 Thirteenth\nstreet N.E.; Pic. John H. Chase. 1425\nFifth street N.W Pfc. Herman Anderson.\n532 Twenty-fourth street N.W.; S/Sergt.\nEmmett J. Hamlin. 1369 Michigan avenue\nN.E.; S/Sergt. George W. Locke. 3645 New\nHampshire ave. N.W.; T/4 Porter E. Swan.\n115 Upshur atreet N.W.; T/3 Joseph B.\nChambers, jr.. 4409 Ord street N.E.: Pic\nWarren G. Carter, 618 Sixth street S.W.:\nPfc. Clarence E. Clark. 6319 Marlboro\nJike S.E.: Pfc Hawes Hill 916 East Cap\nitol street; 1st Sergt. William G. Krause,\n502 Maryland avenue S.W.: Pfc Arguster\nKnolton, 1410 Eleventh street N.W Pvt\nOonaid Oliver. 1320 Eleventh street N.W.:\nPfc. Arthur W. Cloer. 710 East Capitol\nstreet; Pfc. John E. Dean, 24 R atreet\n<.E.; Pfc. Oua N. Condlas, Washington;\nPvt. James A. Smith, 54'! Irving street\n'J.W.; T/4 Mvron M. Jackson. 606 Gre\niham place N.W.; Sergt. Clarence H. Bie\n