 Anderson. 1744\nEighth street N.W.; Corpl. Alvin H. Daingle.\n1124 Eleventh street N.W.: Corpl. Ernest\nRicchiuti. 40 New York avenue N.B.: Pvt.\nCharles A. MacWhirt. 541 Fourth street\n8.E. S Sergt. Robert R. Helm. 727 Sixth\nstreet N.B.: S/Sergt. Spencer B. Lisenby.\n10 Hamilton street N.E.: S/Sergt. Richard\nS. Farr. Washington: Pvt. Wilmer C. New\nton, 943 G street S.W.; Corpl. Abraham\nPollls. 4321 Haley place S.E Pfc. Paul R.\nGreen. lUlfi Bennlng road N.E Corpl.\nAlfred D Lanier. 11 Tennessee avenue\nN E M Sergt. William R. Lansdowne,\n5813 Fourteenth street N.W. Lt Col.\nThomas 8 Barnes. Washington: Maj. Wil\nliam H. Dodderidge. 2900 Connecticut\navenue N.W.\nReturnees\nNinety-six more Washington area\nmen are listed among veterans ar\nriving at East Coast debarkation\nports.\nOf these, the fallowing 33 are due\nto reach Camp Patrick Henry, Va.,\ntomorrow aboard the transport\nMonticello:\nT/4 Jack Swetman, 631 East Oapitol\nstreet; T/5 Charles A. Durkin. 140 U\nstreet N.B.; \u03a4/\u03b4 Clarence L. Wyche. 1600\nTrinidad avenue N.B.; S/Sergt. Roy L.\nJones, 1825 New Hampshire avenue N.W.;\nT/4 Louis J. Lincoln, 8450 Old Fort road\nS.E.; 1st 8ergt. Ned E. Delamar, Jr.. 3915\nEighth street S.E.: Pic. William P. Lyons,\n28 Buchanan street N.B.: Sergt. Wllburn\nC. Smith, 147 D street S.E. Cord. Stanley\nL. Hagan, 4045 Hagan road. Temple Hills.\nMd.: Pic. Ray L. Odis. 1335 Shepherd\nstreet N.B.. Pfc. Nathan Rubinstein, 119\nIngraham street N.W.: Mal. Walter J. D.\nHewitt, 2150 Georgetown road N.W.; War\nrant Officer (J. g.) Morris R. FlUgerald,\n481\u00bb Forty-second street N.W.; 1st Sergt.\nWilliam S. Settle. 1760 Lang place N.B.;\nPic. Richard A. Carr, 4604 Sergeant road\nN.B.; Pic. John C. Welch, 716 Kearney\nstreet N.B.; 1st Sergt. Percy Daniels. 4208\nArkansas avenue N.W Pic. Joseph M\nLizii. 501 Fern place li.W.; MaJ. Charles\nP. Clark, 3101 Wisconsin avenue N.W.;\nT/4 Elmer C. McGuigan, Jr., 1911 U place\nN.B.; Pfc. Louis C. Burch. 2737 Sixth street\nN.W.; Capt. David Cohen. 1736 Trinidad\navenue N.E.; 1st Lt. Frank P. Sanders,\n5429 Connecticut avenue N.W.: Pfc John\nJ. Western, 125 Tenth street N.B.\nNo street addresses were given for\nthe following Washington area men\narriving on the Monticello:\nMaj. Gen. Charles L. Bolte, Brig. Gen.\nHarry B. Sherman. Col. John D. Forsythe.\nCapt. Donald R. Burke. 1st Lt. John H.\nAnderson and 1st Lt. Clifford H. Bailey,\nall of whom gave their addresses as the\nWar Department, and T/Sergt. William G.\nFrankman. jr.. and Sergt. Roy \u039f Senger.\nboth of Washington, and Corpl. George T.\nThomas, Alexandria.\nArrived at Camp Patrick Henry\nyesterday:\nSergt. W. C. Dudgins. 1029 G street N.B.;\nSergt. John M. Wyatt. 60 Defrees streel\nN.W.; Corpl. Isaac D. Clover. 1340 Ver\nmont avenue N.W.: Corpl. James W. Jones\n768 Gresham place N.W.: Pfc. Henry D\nFetterlough. \u00ab09 Florida avenue N.E.; Pfc\nHerbert T. Wass, 1114 Fourth street N.W.;\nPvt. James A. Thomas, 2625 Shermar\navenue N.W.\nT/4 Court P. Allen. Pfc. William J\nCole. Pvt. Archie Jackson. Pfc. John R\nWilliams. 8/Sergt. Nell L. Paircloth, all ol\nWashington, and Pfc. Elden M. Campbel\nand dpt. Thomas M. Draney, both \u03b2 I\nI Alexandria.\nArrived et Boston yesterday\naboard the Pitta ton Victory:\nEergt. Mitchel D. Zatanls. \u03a4/\u03b4 Harvey\nM Bronaon. Fie. James \u039f. Robertson. Pvt.\nNelson Burnt. Serft. Wilbur A. Lovlngs.\n\u03a4 '4 John W Bouknlght, T 4 James R\nGunter, lat Lt. Floyd M. Goslow, Chief\nWarrant Officer Albert T. Milan. Corpl.\nLadd Johnson, T/6 Faul Elliot, Fvt. War\nren Carrer. Corpl. Harold E. Hurlbut. T/6\nJoaeph Brett and Pic. Bernard L. Ma\u00b7\nslno. all ol Washintton, and MaJ. Wil\nliam O. Wiles. Alexandria.\nThe Muhlenberg, scheduled to\narrive at New York today, has\ndocked at the Azores for repairs and\nno new arrival date Is available.\nThe following men from this area\nare listed aboard:\nT/8 Saxton T. Howard, 1st Lt. Marcon\nJ Ball, Pie. Theodore L Long, Pic Wil\nliam C. OOonnell. Pic. Joseph F. Young,\n8/Sergt. Thomas H Chase, S'Sertt. James\nF. R-amseur, Sergt. Felix M. Cole. \u03a4/\u03b4\nMilton L Smith and Pfc. Daniel Dodscn.\nall of Washington, and 1st Lt. John D.\nScott, Alexandria.\nArriving aboard the La Crosse\njVictory In New York today:\nPic. John Edson. Pic. James Gibbs.\nPic. Warren H. Hardin. T/3 Domlnick\nF. Ciango. T/4 Norman Savitt, T/4 Wil\nliam R. Spear. Capt. Leonard Sokolower,\nS/Sergt. Donald I Hamilton. T/3 William\nH. Miles. 1st Lt. George F. Peddicord.\n(T/4 Louis Flynn and Pic. Calvin Bailey,\nj all ol Washington, and Corpl. Clarence\nC. Shatter and 1st Lt. Lewis W. Wagfman.\nboth ol Alexandria.\nDue to reach New York Monday\naboard the Sea Pike:\nPvt. Paul D. Hunter. B/8er\u00abt. Ford F.\nMcConnell, 8 Sergt. Leonard C. Gilbert.\nPic. John L. Hartnett and Ffe. James M.\nMallus. all ol Washington, and 8/Sergt.\nGarfield R. Wilkinson, \u03a4/\u03b4 Palmer F. Dodd\nand Pic. William 8. Howie, all ot Alex\nandria.\nDue to arrive in New York today\nis Chief Warrant Officer Lafayette\nPrice of Washington.\n16 Million Debt in 1845\nThe national debt in 1846 was al\u00b7\nmost $16,000,000.\n24 Girls Fight Plan\nOf Boarding House\nFor Reduced Service\nTwenty-four Government gill\ntoday opposed a petition seeking tc\nreduce services at their boarding\nhouse at 1467 Rhode Island avenue\nN.W., against which they had ear\nlier obtained judgments of $50 each\nbecause they did not get Sunday\ndinners.\nTheir attorney, Elmer E. Cum\nmlngs, asserted the petition was not\nbrought in good faith and that the\nowners want to rent the rooms, but\nnot to \"these young ladies.\" He\nasked for dismissal of the action.\nThe hearing, marked by friction\nbetween counsel and frequent fem\ninine giggles, was held in the Rent\nAdministration office In the Force\nSchool and was attended by about\n15 of the girls.\nSal\u00b7 of Property Planned.\nFrancis R. McDonough, conserva\ntor for the estate of Mrs. Mathilda\nMolin, owner of the property, main\ntains the business no longer is a\npaying proposition, and is seeking\nto have the services reduced in\nanticipation of selling it.\nT. Edward Clarke, attorney for the\nestate, said that to operate the prop\nerty as a boarding house it is neces\nsarv in nov V\\n\u00abl. \u03bf\u03b3*\u03bb _\n_ Tv\u00abv u 1MU11UI,\nI and that Mrs. Molin will lose every\ncent if she has to continue to pay.\nHe said Mrs. Molin is 94 years old.\nMr. McDonough testified the run\nning expenses of the house with the\nserving of meals are $1.200 a month,\nbut with the elimination of meals\nthe expenses are only $500 a month.\nHe said it takes $25 a week to take\ncare of Mrs. Molin. He said the\nproperty was appraised at $25,000.\nI Rank Account Attached.\nErnest P. Williams. Rent Control\nAdministration examiner, overruled\na motion by Mr. Cummings attack\nI ing the agency's jurisdiction. Mr.\nj Cummings maintained the case\nshould have been taken to the Muni\ncipal Court.\nj Mr. Clarke revealed that four or\nS five of the girl? had secured an at\ntachment against Mr. McDonough's\nbank account to satisfy the judg\nment handed down September 20 in\nMunicipal Court following the fail\nure of the boarding house manage\nment to supply Sunday dinners. Mr.\nClarke said since the attachment\nthe four or Ave girls \"have not paid\na cent.\"\nI In the suit over the Sunday din\nners the girls charged they failed\nj to receive the meals for seven weeks\nin July and August in violation of\nthe minimum service standards in\nthe Rent Control Act.\n4 Die in Shanghai Fire\nSHANGHAI, Nov. 2 (\u039b\u00bb).\u2014Pour\ni Japanese were burned to death and\n11 were injured in an exploeion and\nfire which destroyed 11 shops. The\nexplosion occurred in a shop full of\ncelluloid toys.\nI\nHoSatt)Fa\"\nChiP\u00bb (Utto Deba\u00abe_\nIn\nI \u25a01\nThe Governor of Maine and the Governor of Idaho try to\nforce the baked potatoes of their respective States on one an\nother at the potato luncheon in the Senate dining room yester\nday. They are (left to right) Horace A. Hildreth, Governor of\nMaine, and Charles C. Gossett, Governor of Idaho.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nBy GEOKuE KENNEDY.\nSmall potatoes! The inference\nalmost caused blows under the Capi\ntol dome.\nWhen Charles C. Gossett, Gover\nnor of Idaho, spoke of Maine pota\ntoes as peanuts in size, Maine's Gov\nernor, Horace A. Hildreth, cast\namenities aside.\n\"It had been my intention to\nI limit my remarks to the nutritional\naspects of the one truly great potato\n\u2014the Maine potato,\" said Gov. Hil\ndreth. \"But the Governor of Idaho\n!ias chosen to keep his discussion\nclose to the ground\u2014in the dirt, in\nfact.\n\"I shall speak plainly. Let the\nchips fall where they may. This\nis no place for half-baked utter\nances such as you have just heard.\n\"The Governor of Idaho says it\nis a matter of common knowledge\nthat Idaho potatoes are the largest\npotatoes produced. He says they\nput watermelons to shame. What\nhe neglects to mention is that they\nput all the water they can get into\ntheir spuds. Idaho is the only State\nwhich has successfully crossed the\npotato with the sponge.\nHaving taken the starch out of\nthe Governor of Idaho's remarks,'\npermit me to leave you with thi\nbit of advice:\n\"To enjoy the potato is to ea\nthe Maine potato. Not only do the;\nsurpass all self-styled competitor\nin size and flavor, they give yoi\nvitamin C, vitamin B, iron and min\nerals and plenty of dynamic energy.\nThe occasion was the Maine-Idahi\npotato luncheon arranged yesterda:\nin the Senate dining room by Sen\ntor Brewster. Republican, of Maine\nHe brought the two Governors heri\nfor the potato debate. And he ha<\nfour ladies of the House, Repre\nsentatives Douglas. Democrat, \u03bf\nCalifornia; Douglas, Democrat, \u03bf\nIlinois; Rogers, Republican, of Mass\nachusetts, and Luce, Republican, \u03bf\nConnecticut to choose between th<\nbaked Maine potato and the bakec\nIdaho potato.\nThey split on sectional and politi\ncal lines. The New England Repub\u00b7\nlican Representatives were foi\nMaine. The Western Democrat)\nwere for Idaho. They finally decidec\ngood taste demanded a draw.\nController General Lindsay War\nren. who hails from Washington\nN. C., was the fifth judge. He gavi\nthe verdict. The best potato, he said\nwas the North Carolina spud.\nIndonesia\nContinued Prom First Page.)\ni political situation, Dutch economic\nI experts were attempting to compile\ncomplete information on current\n\u03b9 Indonesian economic conditions.\nLack of a proper inventory of\nj what the Japanese left of the\nj Netherlands Indies production sys\ntem makes it impossible to make a\ndefinite statement regarding future\ndevelopments, said A. Luytjes, agri\ncultural chief of the Economic\nAffairs Department.\nQuinine production was best pre\nserved, because the Japanese them\nselves were interested in it, he\nsaid. The rubber plantations came\nthrough rather well, he added, with\nonly minor areas converted into\nvegetable fields. The Indies formerly j\nsupplied 40 per cent of the world's\nrubber demand, and probably will\nbe back at full capacity production\nas soon as normal conditions return,\nhe said.\nNegotiations Unauthorized,\nDutch Government Says\nTHE HAGUE, Nov. 2 tJP\\.\u2014The\nDutch government, referring to a\nconference held Wednesday night\nby Lt. Gov. Hubertus J. van Mook\nand Soekarno, said yesterday that\nif Van Mook was negotiating with\nthe self-styled \"Indonesian Presi\ndent,\" he was \"doing so against the\nexpress wish and instructions of the\ngovernment.\"\nMan, 76, Critically Hurt\nHarry S. Stailey, 76, of 1306 F\nstreet NX. was in critical condition\ntoday from injuries suffered yester\nday when struck by a streetcar at\nSeventh and D streets N.W.\nPolice said the streetcar was op\nerated by Pred T. Carpenter, 53, of\n5613 Seventh street N.W. Mr. Stailey\nwas admitted to the hospital withj\npossible head and internal Injuries.\nRetrial Hearing Delayed\nIn Epes Murder Case\nBy the Associated Press.\nCOLUMBIA, S. C., Nov. 2.\u2014Hear\ning on tne retrial motion of Samue\nC. Epes of Richmond. Va., convictee\nSeptember 22 of murder in the deati\nof his wife, has been postponec\nuntil December 14.\nEpes, 27, was sentenced to lift\nimprisonment when he was grantee\nmercy by the jury that found hin\nguilty on charges of giving his wife\nan overdose of a drug last Januarj\nand burying her in an abandonee\nfoxhole.\nHe immediately moved for a ne*\ntrial and the motion was to have\nbeen heard today before Judge\nArthur Lee Gaston.\nEdgar A. Brown, defense attorney\nsaid he needed more time to have\na transcript of the trial put to\ngether.\nScreams of Witnesses\nCursing Yamashita\nPut Trial in Turmoil\nBt the Associated PrcM.\nMANILA, \u039d\u03bf\\\u03af 2.\u2014Chinese, Fili\npino and Spanish witnesses who\nhysterically cursed the Japanese\nand screamed for the death of Lt.\nGen. Tomoyuki Yamashita, threw\nthe war criminal trial of the former\nPhilippines commander in chief in\ncontinual turmoil today.\nMembers of the prosecution staff\nand interpreters both were required\nto quiet a Chinese woman whose\n4-year-old son had been snatched\nfrom her arms and repeatedly bayo\nneted.\nThe woman testified she had lost\nnine of the 12 in her family and had\nseen women and children slain and\nravaged when 39 Chinese were herd\ned in a lumber yard and murdered\nlast February 10.\n\"I'd like to kill that Japanese\nman,\" she screamed in Chinese at\nYamashita as she finished her testi\nmony and leaped to her feet.\n\"That Jap is to blame for every\nthing. He's got to be killed to pay\nfor what he's done.\"\nScenes \"so bestial it is hard to\nfind words to describe them,\" were\nrelated by witnesses of the mass\nslaying of from 500 to 1,000 civilians\nwho had taken refuge in ihe Manila\nnprman r*lnh r\\r\\ t V->o t-omo\n>1 Spanish Francisco Lopez, former\nMetro-Goldwyn-Mayer representa\ntive in the Philippines, shouted that\nall Japanese soldiers were \"sadists\nand beasts'' as he testified that\ni| Yamashita's troops poured gasoline\n\u25a0lover women's heads and set them\nafire, made sport of young girls for\n\u03b9 the entertainment of other Jap\nanese at a club and then assaulted\none of the girls after she was dead.\nAnother Spaniard, Jose Maldo\nnado, described the tossing of a\nI hand grenade into a bathroom\nI where the Japanese had locked up\nall the men of a group of 50 who\nsought refuge in a certain home.\nFive were killed and many maimed.\nHe said his wife, 22-year-old Ma\nria. was stabbed in the back witn a\nbayonet, the point sticking out 2\ninches from her chest.\nAn elderly Spaniard glared hard\nI at Yamashita as he told of beinR\n\u03b9 wounded in the bathroom and then\nj stumbling out into the kitchen.\nTYIIVAC 44C 1UU11U LlliCC WUlilCil WI1U\nhad been misused by the Japanese\nand then slain.\nA pretty 21-year-old Filipino girl,\nwho exhibited a horribly scared leg,\ntestified how she and some 50 others\nhad been shut in a walled yard,\nihe entrances set afire and grenades\nthrown at them. She escaped by\nrunning through the flames.\nDetails of the slaying of Albeit\nC. Delfino, Venezuelan consul; his\nwife and foster son, on February 13\nwere related by a witness who said\nthey and six others were tied,\nmarched into a room of their home\nand shot. The house was burned.\nThe victims were all robbed before\nthey were slain, the witness said.\nA guard at the home of Carlos\nPerez Rubio, well-known Philippines\nbusinessman who was killed as the\n\u03b9 Japanese fired his home, said Rubio\nwas shot five times as he attempted\nI to escape.\nA nurse who had attended Brig.\nGen. Carl Nathorst. retired officer\nof toe Philippine Constabulary, said\nshe last saw the aged general and\nhis wife and daughter among those\nwho were trapped in the German\nclub. She did not know their fate,\n(but. has not seen them since.\nOur Anniversary Special\nSilver Cigarette\nLIGHTER\nRe/\u03be. Price $